l name from Essworthy in Hatherleigh (Devon). The spelling of the surname reflects the traditional pronunciation of the placename."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Esseby was born about 1260, in Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Joan de Coudray about 1284, in Easby, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1300."},"et":{"Abt 1260–BEF 1300":"umbes 1260–enne 1300","1262–1299":"1262–1299","1285–1306":"1285–1306","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1260–1300":"1260–1300","Abt 1284":"umbes 1284","Abt 1260":"umbes 1260","ABT 1285":"umbes 1285","ABT 1287":"umbes 1287","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","BEF 1300":"enne 1300","1287":"1287","1285":"1285","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1306":"1306","Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Easby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Easby,York,England":"Easby, Yorkshire, England","of Worleston, Cheshire, England":"Worleston, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1260–BEF 1300":"noin 1260–ennen vuotta 1300","1262–1299":"1262–1299","1285–1306":"1285–1306","1287–